==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Epic
<hw>Ep"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>epicus</ets>,
Gr. <?/, from <?/ a word, speech, tale, song; akin to L. <ets>vox</ets>
voice: cf. F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧pique</ets>. See <er>Voice</er>.]</ety>
<def>Narrated in a grand style; pertaining to or designating a kind of
narrative poem, usually called an heroic poem, in which real or
fictitious events, usually the achievements of some hero, are narrated
in an elevated style.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>epic</qex> poem treats of one great, complex action, in a
grand style and with fullness of detail.</q> <rj><qau>T.
Arnold.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Epic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Epic
<hw>Ep"ic</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An epic or heroic poem. See
<er>Epic</er>, <pos>a.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Epical</ent>⟦br⟧
